node.text:
Have you ever gone on a trip where you didn't know the destination? Just said.. YES?
That was my last project in Santa Fe on assignment for @CapitalOne . Diving back into the culture, the food and the incredible nature New Mexico has to offer reminded me a lot of my childhood exploring this area. 
I was working on the launch of the new Venture X card that allows people to do what they love wherever and whenever that may be. For me it looked a bit like the REEL above. On location we enjoyed the milky way above Diablo Canyon, endless singletrack and an epic stay at Bishops Lodge to celebrate Venture X’s 10X earn on hotels booked through Capital One Travel.

#capitalonepartner

The Long Way Around

What we have here isn’t your typical bike trip. Four close friends ventured into the great woods of the American west to experience the land via bike. Their original plans thwarted due to the devastation of wildfires that seemly strike the west more and more each year. With some last-minute rearranging of the route and a nod that it was safe, the ride was on! They took off to experience a ride and hike that some might call, downright insanity.

now playing 

It is not enough to be busy. We must always be engaged, at capacity. We fill in the empty spaces of our daily lives with the superficial. We live in a way that erroneously equates speed and efficiency to value and worth. 

But what happens when we slow down? We value the price of our lives as the time we spend instead of the time we save.  
 
Take the time to invest in the slowness around you. Explore the texture of the world and the playfulness of the ordinary.

This summer solstice I focused on one goal: riding from dawn until dusk, from San Francisco to Yosemite with my compadre @dylanbuffington & @pasnormalstudios
 
This is our Road to Nowhere

Join us for a film premier of “Spirit of the Peaks” at the studio this Tuesday (1/4) at 6pm! Food truck on hand so grab tickets, dress warm, and come watch this awesome film. Tickets are $10 and can be purchased now on Eventbrite or at the door on Tuesday. 

“Spirit of the Peaks” (@spiritofthepeaks) is a film about the struggle for balance between two worlds. For Hunkpapa Lakota skier Connor Ryan (@sacredstoke), skiing in Ute Territory has always raised questions about being in reciprocity with the land and its people. As a skier who connects with the land through sport, he empathizes with the injustices that have displaced the Utes and ongoing colonization, erasure and extraction impacting the Ute people. This story connects conflicted pasts to an awakening in cultural awareness that can create an equitable future for Indigenous people and skiers. The film was produced in partnership with @Wondercamp.co and @NativesOutdoors

node.text:
I needed a bike that could take me to the end of the Earth and back. There were moments of pure hell and moments of total bliss & at times they seemed to blend together. I would never recommend it,  but I hadn’t actually seen or ridden the bike before I arrived in Iceland. It was a total gamble and I had to trust my friends at @fezzari_bicycles basically with my life and the expectation that their new KINGS PEAK would perform in all conditions. Luckily it outperformed my expectations, even when the temps hit -24F on the top of the glacier while we pushed out bikes for 7 hours. 

Grateful to say that the KINGS PEAK Fatbike is out now! Felt honored to test this bike in such harsh and gnarly conditions. 

📷 @_ryanhill_
